    sections: [
      { heading: "The Babylonian Method for Square Roots", body: "The Babylonian method, also known as Heron's method, is an ancient algorithm that converges rapidly to accurate square roots. Start with an initial guess, then repeatedly apply the formula: next guess equals current guess plus the number divided by current guess, all divided by two. To find the square root of fifty, guess seven. Fifty divided by seven is approximately seven point one four. Add seven and seven point one four to get fourteen point one four, then divide by two to get seven point zero seven. Repeating the process with seven point zero seven gives an even more precise result. After just two or three iterations, the answer is accurate enough for most practical purposes." },
      { heading: "Estimation Through Perfect Squares", body: "Finding square roots by estimation uses your knowledge of perfect squares. Since seven squared is forty-nine and eight squared is sixty-four, the square root of fifty must be between seven and eight. The distance from forty-nine to fifty is one, while the total gap from forty-nine to sixty-four is fifteen. A linear approximation adds one-fifteenth to seven, giving approximately seven point zero seven. This estimation method works for any number: identify the nearest perfect squares below and above, then interpolate. The accuracy decreases for numbers far from perfect squares, but the method provides a quick mental approximation that is often sufficient for everyday calculations and checking work." },
      { heading: "Prime Factorization Method", body: "Prime factorization finds square roots of perfect squares by breaking the number into its prime factors. Factor the number into primes, then pair identical factors. The square root is the product of one factor from each pair. For example, one hundred forty-four factors into two times two times two times two times three times three. Pairing them gives two pairs of two and one pair of three. The square root is two times two times three, which equals twelve. This method works perfectly for perfect squares but cannot produce exact results for non-perfect squares. However, it helps identify whether a number is a perfect square and provides exact integer square roots when they exist." },
      { heading: "Long Division Style Square Root Algorithm", body: "The long division method for square roots provides exact results digit by digit, similar to long division. Group the digits of the number in pairs starting from the decimal point. Find the largest number whose square is less than or equal to the first group. Subtract and bring down the next pair. Double the current result and find a digit to append such that the product of the resulting number and that digit is less than or equal to the current remainder. Repeat until you reach the desired precision. This method is more tedious than the Babylonian method but produces exact decimal representation and works for any precision level. It is the algorithm most early calculators used internally." },
      { heading: "Practical Applications of Manual Square Root Calculations", body: "Manual square root calculation remains valuable despite ubiquitous calculators. In standardized tests that do not allow calculators, these methods are essential for math sections. Geometry problems frequently require square roots for diagonal distances, areas, and the Pythagorean theorem. Physics calculations for velocity, acceleration, and wave properties often involve square roots. Statistics uses square roots for standard deviation calculations. In carpentry and construction, square roots help calculate diagonal bracing lengths and material quantities. Understanding manual methods also builds numerical intuition: knowing that the square root of two is approximately one point four one four helps you quickly estimate diagonal distances and recognize unreasonable calculator errors." }
    ]
